'''Fuka-Arthur Masuaku Kawela''' (born 7 November 1993) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[left-back]] or [[centre-back]] for {{French football updater|Lens}} club [[RC Lens|Lens]], on loan from [[Premier League]] club [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]. Born in France, he plays for the [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo national team]].

Masuaku began his senior career with [[Valenciennes FC|Valenciennes]], and has also played for [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]], [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] and [[Beşiktaş J.K.|Beşiktaş]]. He represented France at youth level before switching his allegiance to DR Congo in 2017.

== Early life ==
Masuaku was born in [[Lille]], France, to DR [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Congolese]] parents.<ref name="FFF" /> He acquired [[French nationality law|French nationality]] on 20 April 2006, through the collective effect of his mother's [[naturalization]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=JORF n° 0095 du 22 avril 2006 – Légifrance |url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/jorf/jo/2006/04/22/0095 |access-date=2024-01-02 |website=legifrance.gouv.fr |page=6105 |language=fr |format=PDF}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Valenciennes===
Masuaku came through the youth system of [[Valenciennes FC|Valenciennes]]. He made his [[Ligue 1]] debut on the opening game of the [[2013–14 Ligue 1|2013–14 season]] on 10 August 2013 against [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]]. He was substituted after 75 minutes for [[Tongo Doumbia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/match/292571 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620195152/http://www.lequipe.fr/Football/match/292571 |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 20, 2013 |title=Valenciennes–Toulouse: 3–0 |date=10 August 2014 |access-date=15 July 2014}}</ref> On 29 January 2014 Masuaku scored his first competitive goal for Valenciennes in a 2–1 away defeat against [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Marseille-valenciennes-2-1/436398 |title=Marseille–Valenciennes: 2–1 |date=29 January 2014 |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref>

===Olympiacos===
In July 2014, Masuaku signed for [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.olympiacos.org/article/37997/paiktis-toy-olympiakoy-o-mazoyakoy|script-title=el:Παίκτης του Ολυμπιακού ο Μαζουακού |date=22 July 2014 |language=el |publisher=Olympiacos.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.footmercato.net/breves/info-fm-masuaku-s-engage-avec-l-olympiacos_133749?KeepThis=true&TB_iframe=true&height=530&width=900 |title=Info FM : Masuaku s'engage avec l'Olympiacos!|trans-title=Info FM: Masuaku signs for Olympiacos |date=7 July 2014 |access-date=11 July 2014 |language=fr |publisher=Footmercato.net}}</ref> He made his [[Super League Greece|Super League]] debut against [[Niki Volos F.C.|Niki Volos]], and in his third league match he provided two assists against [[OFI Crete F.C.|OFI]] in a 3–0 home win.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sport24.gr/football/omades/Olympiakos/olympiakos_-_ofh_3-0.3024171.html |title=Ολυμπιακός–ΟΦΗ 3–0 |date=13 September 2014 |publisher=Sport24 |access-date=12 January 2015}}</ref> Three days later he made his debut and scored in the [[UEFA Champions League]] competition against [[Atlético Madrid]] in a 3–2 home win.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/sep/16/olympiakos-atletico-madrid-champions-league-match-report |title=Olympiakos gain surprise win over 2014 beaten finalists Atlético Madrid |date=16 September 2014 |newspaper=The Guardian |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140919172344/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/sep/16/olympiakos-atletico-madrid-champions-league-match-report |archive-date=September 19, 2014}}</ref>

In April and May 2015, interest from [[A.S. Roma|Roma]], [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]] and [[Juventus FC|Juventus]] was reported.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sdna.gr/gr/news-in-english/arthro-news-in-english/35383/massuaku-in-roma-shortlist/ |title=Masuaku in Roma shortlist |date=8 May 2015 |publisher=www.sdna.gr |access-date=31 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510081711/http://www.sdna.gr/gr/news-in-english/arthro-news-in-english/35383/massuaku-in-roma-shortlist/ |archive-date=10 May 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.football-italia.net/65807/inter-enquire-masuaku |title=Inter enquire for Masuaku |date=29 April 2015 |publisher=www.football-italia.net}}</ref> His agent, Roger Henrotay, however stated a renewal of Masuaku's contract was on the cards.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sdna.gr/gr/news-in-english/arthro-news-in-english/37267/masuaku-set-for-new-olympiakos-contract/ |title=Masuaku set for new Olympiakos contract |date=16 May 2015 |publisher=www.sdna.gr |access-date=31 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518210246/http://www.sdna.gr/gr/news-in-english/arthro-news-in-english/37267/masuaku-set-for-new-olympiakos-contract/ |archive-date=18 May 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In July, a reported €4 million offer for Masuaku including former Olympiacos midfielder [[Giannis Fetfatzidis]] from [[Genoa CFC|Genoa]] was rejected by the club.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.calciomercato.com/news/genoa-su-masuaku-il-rifiuto-non-spaventa-preziosi-279888 |title=Genoa su Masuaku: la trattativa |date=15 July 2015 |publisher=www.calciomercato.com}}</ref>

===West Ham United===
[[File:Hertha BSC vs. West Ham United 20190731 (185).jpg|thumb|upright|Masuaku warming up before a match in 2019]]

On 8 August 2016, Masuaku joined [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] on a four-year contract for a £6.2 million fee.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.whufc.com/News/Articles/2016/August/8-August/Hammers-acquire-Arthur |title=Hammers acquire Arthur |date=8 August 2014 |access-date=8 August 2016 |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809141741/http://www.whufc.com/News/Articles/2016/August/8-August/Hammers-acquire-Arthur |archive-date=9 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lustig |first1=Nick |title=West Ham sign Arthur Masuaku from Olympiacos |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11685/10527846/west-ham-sign-arthur-masuaku-from-olympiacos |access-date=8 August 2016 |work=Sky Sports |date=8 August 2016}}</ref> He made his West Ham debut in a 2–1 away defeat to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on 15 August 2016. Masuaku admitted that he found his Premier League debut very tough due to the pace and physicality of the league.<ref name="whudebut">{{cite news |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2016/august/16-august/masuaku-big-week-club |title=Masuaku – This is a big week for the Club |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |date=16 August 2016 |access-date=28 January 2018}}</ref> He scored his first goal for West Ham in an [[EFL Cup]] tie against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] on 19 September 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41235277 |title=West Ham 3–0 Bolton |publisher=BBC |date=19 September 2017 |access-date=20 September 2017}}</ref>

In the FA Cup fourth round game against [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] on 27 January 2018, Masuaku was sent off for spitting at Wigan's [[Nick Powell]] following a challenge.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42756107 |title=Wigan Athletic 2–0 West Ham United |date=27 January 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> It was the first sending-off of Masuaku's career. Masuaku apologised for the sending off, saying the incident was "totally unacceptable and out of character".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42853262 |title=West Ham: Arthur Masuaku apologises for spitting in FA Cup defeat |date=28 January 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He received a six match ban for the offence.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42860274 |title=Arthur Masuaku: West Ham defender gets six-game ban for spitting |date=29 January 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=29 January 2018}}</ref>

In July 2019, having played 75 times for West Ham, Masuaku signed a contract extension with the club until 2024 with an option to further extend the contract for two years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49155216|title=West Ham defender Arthur Masuaku signs contract extension to 2024|work=BBC Sport |date=July 29, 2019}}</ref>

On 4 December 2021, Masuaku scored the winning goal in a 3–2 victory over defending [[UEFA Champions League]] winners [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]. The goal, a mishit cross that caught out Chelsea goalkeeper [[Edouard Mendy]] at his near post, was his only [[Premier League]] goal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59380844 |title=West Ham 3–2 Chelsea|date=4 December 2021 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2021/12/04/west-ham-vs-chelsea-live-score-premier-league-latest-updates/|title=Arthur Masuaku's freakish late goal completes West Ham comeback to stun Chelsea|first1=Matt|last1=Law|first2=Rob|last2=Bagchi|newspaper=The Telegraph |date=December 4, 2021|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>

=== Beşiktaş ===
On 2 August 2022, Masuaku joined Turkish team [[Beşiktaş J.K.|Beşiktaş]] on a season long loan with an option to buy in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/arthur-masuaku-joins-besiktas-loan|title=Arthur Masuaku joins Beşiktaş on loan &#124; West Ham United F.C.|website=www.whufc.com}}</ref> On 17 April 2023, Masuaku completed a permanent transfer to [[Beşiktaş J.K.|Beşiktaş]].<ref name="West Ham transfer">{{cite web | title=Arthur Masuaku completes permanent Beşiktaş transfer | website=West Ham United F.C. | url=https://www.whufc.com/news/arthur-masuaku-completes-permanent-besiktas-transfer | access-date=17 April 2023}}</ref> The fee was undisclosed by the clubs but was reported by some sources to be in the region of £2million.<ref name="Thomas 2023">{{cite web | last=Thomas | first=Oliver | title=West Ham United left-back Arthur Masuaku joins Besiktas on permanent deal | website=Sports Mole | date=17 April 2023 | url=https://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/west-ham-united/transfer-talk/news/west-hams-arthur-masuaku-joins-besiktas-on-permanent-deal_511629.html?t=123987456&s=zero | access-date=17 April 2023}}</ref>

On 30 June 2025, Beşiktaş announced Masuaku's departure from the club.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bjk.com.tr/tr/haber/91919/arthur-masuakuya-tesekkur-ederiz.html |title=Arthur Masuaku’ya Teşekkür Ederiz|publisher=Beşiktaş J.K. |access-date=30 June 2025}}</ref>

=== Sunderland ===
On 10 August 2025, Masuaku signed a two-year contract with Premier League club [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]].<ref>{{cite web | last=Brotherton | first=Alex | title=Arthur Masuaku: Sunderland sign former West Ham left-back | website=BBC Sport | date=10 August 2025 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cd6ng6dxw99o | access-date=10 August 2025}}</ref>

On 27 January 2026, Masuaku joined [[RC Lens|Lens]] in [[Ligue 1]], where he already played as a youth, on loan until the end of the 2025–26 season.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=RC Lens|url=https://www.rclens.fr/fr/news/mercato-arthur-masuaku-rclens-contrat-20260127|title=Arthur Masuaku, un joueur de devoir dans le couloir|trans-title=Arthur Masuaku, a duty player in the corridor|date=27 January 2026|access-date=28 January 2026|language=fr}}</ref>

==International career==
Having represented [[France national football team|France]] at [[France national under-18 football team|under-18]] and [[France national under-19 football team|under-19]] level,<ref name=FFF>{{cite web |url=http://www.fff.fr/equipes-de-france/tous-les-joueurs/fiche-joueur/1916827592-arthur-masuaku |title=Arthur Masuaku |publisher=Fédération Française de Football |access-date=12 January 2015 |archive-date=15 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190615025331/https://www.fff.fr/equipes-de-france/tous-les-joueurs/fiche-joueur/1916827592-arthur-masuaku |url-status=dead }}</ref> Masuaku switched his allegiance to [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]] in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://foot.cd/west-ham-arthur-masuaku-jouer-rdc/ |title=West Ham: Arthur Masuaku peut jouer avec la RDC — FOOT.CD |website=foot.cd |date=16 June 2017 |access-date=10 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afrik-foot.com/can-2019-la-liste-de-la-rdc-contre-le-congo |title=CAN 2019 : la liste de la RDC contre le Congo |website=Afrik-foot.com |date=26 May 2017 |access-date=10 August 2017}}</ref> In August 2017, he was called into his first DR Congo squad, for two [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification|2018 World Cup qualification]] games against [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2017/august/10-august/masuaku-receives-first-dr-congo-call |title=Masuaku receives first DR Congo call-up |website=www.whufc.com |access-date=10 August 2017}}</ref> In March 2018, still yet to make his international debut, Masuaku travelled with the DR Congo squad for a friendly against Tanzania. He was one of four players to drop out before the game, amidst claims of organisational problems and travel disorder, and did not appear.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Masuaku leaves DR Congo squad early amid travel frustration claims |first=James |last=Benge |work=London Evening Standard |date=26 March 2018 |access-date=21 June 2018 |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/west-ham-s-arthur-masuaku-leaves-dr-congo-squad-early-amid-claims-of-travel-frustration-a3799521.html}}</ref> He made his debut on 13 October 2018, starting in a 1–2 home loss against [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]] in a [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] game.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/october/13-october/masuaku-makes-dr-congo-bow-zimbabwe-defeat |title=Masuaku makes DR Congo bow in Zimbabwe defeat – West Ham United |website=www.whufc.com |access-date=14 October 2018}}</ref> Masuaku scored his first goal for DR Congo, a [[free-kick]], in a 1–1 away draw with [[Kenya national football team|Kenya]] on 15 June 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2019/june/15-june/masuaku-scores-first-dr-congo-goal-kenya-draw |title=Masuaku scores first DR Congo goal in Kenya draw – West Ham United |website=www.whufc.com |access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref>

===2023 Africa Cup of Nations===
On 27 December 2023, Masuaku was included in the final 24-man squad for the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.afrik-foot.com/rdc-liste-can-2023-desabre| title= ARDC : la liste de 24 pour la CAN 2023 dévoilée !|date=27 December 2023}}</ref> He started his nation's first match at the tournament, a 1–1 draw with [[Zambia national football team|Zambia]] on 17 January 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cafonline.com/caf-africa-cup-of-nations/match-centre?competition=190&season=2023&match=2411936|title=Congo DR 1–1 Zambia|website=CAF Online|date=17 January 2024|accessdate=21 January 2024}}</ref> He went on to score in his nation's 3–1 victory over [[Guinea national football team|Guinea]] in the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations knockout stage#DR Congo vs Guinea|quarter-finals]] on 2 February 2024. It booked DR Congo a place in the semi-finals of the AFCON for the first time since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20240202-masuaku-free-kick-clinches-afcon-semi-finals-place-for-dr-congo|title=Masuaku free-kick clinches AFCON semi-finals place for DR Congo|website=France24|date=2 February 2024|accessdate=6 February 2024}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Masuaku is a practising Muslim.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/west-ham-united-celebrates-ramadan |title=West Ham United celebrates Ramadan |publisher=whufc.com |access-date=30 April 2022}}</ref> In June 2025, he made the [[Umrah]] pilgrimage to [[Mecca]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://spor.haber7.com/besiktas/haber/3542150-besiktas-ile-sozlesmesi-biten-yildiz-umreye-gitti |title=Beşiktaş ile sözleşmesi biten yıldız Umre'ye gitti! |publisher=haber7spor |access-date=26 June 2025}}</ref>

